# Vercel Speed Insights Implementation

Successfully installed and configured Vercel Speed Insights for this Next.js 14.2.5 App Router project.

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed Package
- Installed `@vercel/speed-insights@^1.3.1` using npm
- Package added to dependencies in package.json

### 2. Modified Files

#### src/app/layout.tsx
- Added import: `import { SpeedInsights } from "@vercel/speed-insights/next"`
- Added `<SpeedInsights />` component inside the `<body>` tag, after the `<AppShell>` component
- The component is properly placed to track all page navigations in the app

#### .eslintrc.json (Created)
- Created basic ESLint configuration file extending "next/core-web-vitals"
- This allows the linter to run properly (it was previously unconfigured)

#### package.json
- Added `@vercel/speed-insights@^1.3.1` to dependencies

#### package-lock.json
- Updated with new dependency tree for @vercel/speed-insights

## Implementation Details

Since this project uses Next.js 14.2.5 with App Router, I used the recommended approach:
- Imported from `@vercel/speed-insights/next` (automatic route tracking)
- No need for manual route prop or `usePathname()` hook
- Component placed in root layout for app-wide tracking

## Verification

✅ Build completed successfully (31 static pages generated)
✅ ESLint ran successfully on modified layout.tsx (no new errors)
✅ All changes properly integrated with existing code structure
✅ Dependencies installed and lock file updated

The Speed Insights component will now automatically track:
- Page load performance metrics
- Core Web Vitals (LCP, FID, CLS)
- Navigation performance
- All metrics will be visible in the Vercel dashboard when deployed

## Notes

- The implementation preserves all existing code structure
- No breaking changes introduced
- Speed Insights will only send data when deployed to Vercel (no-op in development)
- Pre-existing linting warnings in other files remain unchanged
